data.message: Hello TSP members! Many thanks to those of you who have done our first follow-up survey sent out two weeks ago. For those of you who haven't, don't forget to check your email and complete it for a $20 gift card! You’ll earn an additional $20 at the end if you fill out all surveys!

Thanks! I've gotten $40 for taking two surveys

Just a friendly reminder to check your email and fill out the first follow-up survey that we sent out last week. Remember, you'll receive $20 for completing it and will receive an additional $20 at the end if you complete all follow-up surveys!
Finally, I've been waiting for so long! :)

Hello TSP members! Yesterday, we shared the last post of our 90-day program. Please check your email today for our first follow-up survey. You will receive a $20 gift card upon completion.We hope that our Facebook group has been enjoyable, educational, and life-changing in some way, whether it be a shift in your perspective towards smoking, or a commitment towards a healthier, smoke-free life. All of us at TSP have enjoyed reading your comments and interacting with you online, and we truly thank you for your participation.Although we will no longer be posting daily, you are welcome to remain in this secret group and access all of the content we've shared over the past 90 days. Furthermore, we're still available to answer any questions/concerns about smoking, and we're open to any feedback/suggestions you may have for our program.Again, from all of us at TSP, thank you and good luck in your future endeavors!

Nice to hear your experience that the cravings subside over time. Do you have someone or people in your life who are supporting you?
In addition to us here at TSP, of course ;)

That definitely counts as support. If you haven't told them about your quitting, then it might be a good time to share your success. If there is something specific they can do to support you, let them know.
They all know that I quit but we don't really talk about it.

Well if you think it would be helpful to share how it is going with someone you respect and trust, then definitely go ahead. It is not easy to quit and you should be proud of the work you've done already. Relapse is possible though, so it will be important for you to have some good support in place if it does happen.

I like to leave you guys with tips in these session, so today, here is our 5-step TSP quit plan. See if something resonates with you: 1. GET READY.• Set a quit date and stick to it – not even a single puff! 2. GET SUPPORT AND ENCOURAGEMENT.• Tell your family, friends and coworkers you are quitting.• Talk to your doctor or other health care provider.• Get group, individual, or telephone counseling. Think about who can support you with quitting smoking 3. LEARN NEW SKILLS AND BEHAVIORS.• When you first try to quit, change your routine.• Reduce stress.• Distract yourself from urges to smoke.• Plan something enjoyable to do every day.• Drink a lot of water and other fluids. Think about which of these will be most helpful to you?4. GET MEDICATION AND USE IT CORRECTLY.Talk with your health care provider about which medication will work best for you:• Medication: bupropion, verenicline (prescription).• Nicotine Replacement:-gum and patch are over-the-counter-inhaler and nasal spray are prescriptio Is there one of these that you think would be helpful for you?5. BE PREPARED FOR RELAPSE OR DIFFICULT SITUATIONS.• Avoid alcohol.• Be careful around other smokers.• Improve your mood in ways other than smoking.• Eat a healthy diet and stay active.
Next week Johannes Thrul will be back. It has been a pleasure to do The Dr. Is In sessions for the past few weeks. Thanks, guys!

Hi everyone and welcome to TSP! I am available for the next hour. Let me know if you have any questions!Since you told us at the beginning you are ready to quit smoking, I was wondering if anyone of you may be ready to set a quit date already? (Experts agree this is the most effective way to quit for good) #TDII

Hi 10175 - great to hear that you are ready to set a quit date. This is what happens to many smokers - it can be hard to follow through with a quit date. Part of this intervention is to prepare you to set a quit date and follow through with it. Next week I will also start with a series of smoking cessation advice sessions where I will work with each one of you to come up with your customized quit plan. Is that something you would be interested in?
Yes I would be very interested
I would like to quit by the 15th of this month
That's my goal

Great to hear that 10175 & 10246! In a nutshell these are the things I would recommend (sounds like a lot right now, but we will work on all of these during the course of TSP): 1. Pick a quit day and following through with it. 2. Get support from family/friends/colleagues. 3. Learn new skills and alternative behaviors for your high risk situations. 4. Depending on how much you smoke I would definitely recommend that you consider trying some form of nicotine replacement therapy – we know that using these can dramatically decrease your cravings and withdrawal and increase your chances to quit for good. 5. Be prepared for relapse or difficult situations (e.g., alcohol, being around other smokers, stress, etc.). I know this sounds like a lot, but we will cover each of these aspects more in depth over the next weeks. How does this sound? Anything there you think may be useful?

Thanks for sharing 10175 - I appreciate your honesty! This group is about supporting each other, so you are certainly not going to get any negative comments from me. I think it is great that you have decided to try to quit - and that's the most important thing. With regard to Chantix: I am not an MD and I would recommend you talk to your family doctor or a medical professional you trust - there may be ways for you to use Chantix. Also we can talk more about nicotine replacement therapy. I would be curious to find out more about how you used it before and if a higher dose or a combination of patch and gum may be a good idea in your case. Again, I would recommend you talk to your doctor about that. What do you think?
I had tried the patch a couple years ago and it gave me vivid nightmares. It was awful. I'll try talking to my doctor about it at my next appointment to see if I can use any of them.
10175 - yes this is a great idea! Please keep me posted what they tell you. What do you think about the other steps I have posted earlier? Anything sound like it may be useful?

My family would be supportive, none of them smoke and they have been trying to get me to quit for years. No, I don't think it's too close 10175. I will also do a TDII session next Wednesday where I will check in with you. When is your next doctors appointment where you can find out about your medication options? Also, I think it's a very good idea to talk to your colleagues - you can ask them to not offer you any more cigarettes and not to ask you to smoke with them or smoke while you are around.

Also, I would like to know more about your high risk situations? Which situations get you to light up? And do you have any ideas what you could do instead? Do you have a close friend you could rely on when the craving hits? Someone you can call to support you?

I have an appointment a week from today. I seem to smoke more when I am at school and when I am driving. It's habit for me to just light up a cigarette as soon as I get in the car. I think it's more that I have habits that I have to break than the actual craving being that bad. The dad said he would quit with me so I can call him when I am wanting to smoke.

Ok why don't you talk to him and tell him about your quit plans and about the quit date? We have already talked about the folks at your school and I definitely recommend you talk to them as well so they can support you or at least not make it any more difficult. Let's talk about smoking in your car: What could you do instead? Any alternatives to smoking or something that would distract you? I recommend on the evening before you quit day get rid of your smokes, lighters, everything that reminds you of smoking. Get a new scent for your car or even clean it the day before you quit, that will make smoking less appealing. What else could you do?
I am actually getting the carpets and seats shampooed before I quit so it won't smell like smoke. I used to keep candy in the car when I first got it. It distracted me from smoking

Great! Yes, get candy, gum, toothpicks, anything that you can use to distract yourself. Get some new tunes you like so you can sing along :) and in case you don't have it a hands free device for your phone so you can call someone when it gets really bad. You know most cravings only last 5 minutes, so try to face them one at a time!
How confident do you feel that you can do it?
Great talking to you today guys. I've got to run. Stay tuned for our special smoking cessation advice sessions! I will start them next week. See you soon and keep up the good work!
I haven't smoked for two weeks actually, today I almost asked for a cigarette frm my dad but was able to keep from it

data.message: To finish up, I want to share with you 5 steps that can guide you make a plan when you’re ready to quit:1. GET READY: Set a quit date and stick to it – not even a single puff!I know you have already set a quit data 10175 - that's greatWhen do you think you will be ready 10217?
By the end of this month
Great - if you don't mind I will check in with you over the next couple of weeks in preparation of your quit date.

One thing I recommend both of you 10217 and 10175: You can try some smoking reduction techniques leading up to your quit date. Try different ways to cope with your cravings and get better at not smoking in certain situations. You could for example increase the time interval between cigarettes, decide to not smoke certain cigarettes (e.g., a specific one after a meal, or the first one in the morning, etc.), or declare certain smokefree zones. All of this will be a great preparation for your quit date. What do you think?
Sounds good

That’s all for today’s session!Use the TSP group through your quit date!Also, start discussing your stop smoking goals with the people you listed in Section 2 of your quit plan, and keep your Smoking, Mood, and Activities log updated!Have a great week!
The next "The doctor is in" session will be on Wednesday! I will check in with you then.
Do you have any questions about your quit plan?
No I think it's just going to be a lot of willpower
Agreed 10175! You can do it and we are all here to support you!
Also, I encourage you to practice reducing your smoking and different distraction techniques for dealing with your cravings!
5. BE PREPARED FOR RELAPSE OR DIFFICULT SITUATIONS:- Avoid alcohol- Be careful around other smokers- Improve your mood in ways other than smoking- Eat a healthy diet and stay active
Which of these will be most helpful to you?
What do you think you could do in a difficult situation, like drinking with friends who smoke?
I can't drink at the moment so that's not really a problem, but I have avoided going out to bars with my friends who smoke
I think that's really smart 10175 - especially in the first weeks of quitting smoking!

4. GET MEDICATION AND USE IT CORRECTLY:Talk with your health care provider about which medication will work best for you:- Medication: bupropion, varenicline (prescription).- Nicotine Replacement: gum, patch, or lozenge (over-the-counter), inhaler & nasal spray (prescription)
Are there one of these that you think would be helpful for you?

Great - let me know what you find out, ok?

3. LEARN NEW SKILLS AND BEHAVIORS.- When you first try to quit, change your routine.- Reduce stress.- Distract yourself from urges to smoke.- Plan something enjoyable to do every day.- Drink a lot of water and other fluids.Which of these will be most helpful to you?

2. GET SUPPORT AND ENCOURAGEMENT:- Tell your family, friends and coworkers you are quitting.- Talk to your doctor or other health care provider.- Get group, individual, or telephone counseling.Who can support you with quitting smoking?
I want to show you something we call the “Daily Tracking of Smoking, Mood, and Activities” log.
You can use it to better understand your smoking by tracking your pleasant activities, mood, and cigs smoked each day.

You should keep it in a place where you can see it every day and notice pleasant activities, mood (faces) and cigs.So, where is the best place for you?... An image on your phone? A photo on FB? Printing it and putting in on your fridge or bathroom mirror??
I took a screenshot and set it as my background
Perfect - try it for today as an example…Looking at the Mood log above, what are your stats for today? (You can use an emoticon for the mood if you want)
I can't really think of anything pleasant I've done today. I've smoked 7 cigarettes and I'm kinda

OK, thanks for sharing! The goal is to notice patterns in your pleasant activities, mood, and cigs, so it's important to track them often.As you are thinking about quitting, you want to increase your pleasant activities – this will help you with your mood and with quitting cigarettes. How does that sound?

I know, doing it is probably not quite as easy as it sounds, but it's important to try!
First I'm interested to find out a little about your smoking habits: How much are you smoking right now? Like how many cigs per day? How many days a week?
I smoke at most 10 a day and I smoke every day
Alright, and what are your current goals for quitting?
I'm hoping to completely quit on Wednesday
Awesome!
I smoke at least half a pack every day
Hi 10217, good to have you here. And what are your current goals for quitting?
I want to but it's harder than I hoped
I understand 10217 - it's great that you are willing to give it a try though - and you have a good team to support you :)

10217 try the surveys I have posted and feel free to comment on all other posts here, too!
I will thank you

Now, I want you to take another quick survey, this time about your reasons for quitting: https://ucsf.co1.qualtrics.com/SE/?SID=SV_bHfZzczARW9HBOJWhen you’re done, tell me which categories you scored a 9 or higher.
I scored above a 9 in everything except example

A high score on Health suggests that the hazards of smoking may be enough to make you want to quit now. A high score on Example suggests you want to set a good example for others. A high score in Esthetics suggests you recognize and are disturbed by some of the unpleasant aspects of smoking. A high score in Mastery suggests you are bothered by the fact that you cannot control your desire to smoke.
Does this fit with your personal reasons for quitting?
Yes
Ok good, we have a good idea of why you want to quit and you should remind yourself of those reasons going forward.

Try this SHORT survey about why you smoke (Don’t worry it’s easy)STOP when you get your score. https://ucsf.co1.qualtrics.com/SE/?SID=SV_73dz87ACkEB28vPWhich categories did you score 11 or higher? If you didn’t score 11 or higher in any of them, which were your 2 highest scores?
I got a 14 under crutch and a 9 under addiction and relaxation.
A high score in Crutch: Tension Reduction suggests you use cigarettes as a crutch in moments of stress or discomfort.
A high score in Craving: Psychological Addiction suggests you are psychologically addicted to cigarettes. Quitting smoking is difficult for the person who is psychologically addicted.
Does that fit with why you think you smoke?
Which I know I do a lot

It is really useful to know your reasons for smoking, so you can be aware of your triggers or high risk situations. Remind yourself of those reasons going forward.

data.message: Hi guys, I am getting ready to start with session 3. Stop by if you want to learn about social support and quitting.
Hi guys, I have posted the content of today's session on the wall of this event. Check it out if you're interested! See you next week.

That’s it for today’s session.Between now and next time, practice being assertive. You can do it!Also, keep commenting on your Daily Tracking of Smoking, Mood, and Activities. Use this Pleasant Activities checklist to identify some activities that interest you. See you next time! Bye.

Sometimes you may have to respond by revealing to others how their behavior/comments make you feel. There are 3 steps to being successful with this: 1. Be neutral when describing their behavior to them2. Use “I feel” statements to describe how you feel about their comments/behavior3. Let them know what you want from them (i.e. a specific behavior change) that can help you as you quitHow do you think you could use these 3 steps in your situations to respond assertively?

Although other people may not always change their behavior upon your request, using these steps gives you a better chance of getting what you want and will leave you feeling better about yourself and your ability to be assertive.
Everyone is not the same personality. There are many personal styles of communicating:First is the passive style. Here’s a list:
Next there’s the aggressive style:
There’s one last personality type—the ASSERTIVE type:

By being assertive, you have the best chance of getting what you want and you will feel better about yourself by stating/responding that way.BUT…being assertive does not mean that you always have to speak your mind in every situation.Are there any situations in your pursuit of quitting smoking where you guys would like to be more assertive?

How would you handle the following situations without smoking? 2. You just got out of school. Your friends are smoking.You’re feeling relaxed and thinking about how you always used to smoke at parties.Just as you start to say to yourself, “A cigarette would sure be good now,” your friend offers you a cigarette.What would you do or say?

Think positively about your decision to refuse a cigarette.It is easy to go along with what everyone else is doing.You are someone who makes a decision to do something and sticks to it!Respect yourself, and you will earn the respect of others in the long run.Here’s a pic you can use to remind you of the tips

As your Quit Day approaches, we're going to re-post "The Night Before Checklist" and "On Your Quit Day" series here. No need to comment -- these are just some final tips that we think are helpful :)
The night before your Quit Day, make sure you've gotten rid of all your cigarettes, lighters, matches and ashtrays from your car and home.

The night before your Quit Day, put together a non-smoker survival kit, complete with sugarless gum/candy, toothpicks, other substitutes for smoking, a list of your reasons for quitting, and phone numbers/photos of your support people.
The night before your Quit Day, reflect on the fact that tomorrow will be your first day free from cigarette addiction!
After smoking your last cigarette the night before your Quit Day, take a shower, wash your hair, and brush your teeth. Get rid of all the last traces of nicotine!
